entry.title: Shure Beta91A Kick Drum Mic - Promo Clip

media:group.media:description:
The recently released Shure Beta91A kick drum microphone is a big improvement on 'the old one' - with its integrated microphone preamplifier now removing the need for the external XLR preamplifier, and tethering cable. At just on 500g it's also a little heavier that the original Beta91. Perfect for kick drums on any size stage, and you can also pop this one in pianos, organs and anything else with a big (and low) freqency range.
Of course, for this promo clip one of our favourite customers Hugh shows up looking for a new microphone. We make sure he gets looked after.
For any questions, head over to http://www.factorysound.com
media:group.media:keywords: Shure, Beta91A, kick, drum, microphone, factory, sound, professional, audio, livesound, engineer, miking, stage, studio
media:group.media:title: Shure Beta91A Kick Drum Mic - Promo Clip

entry.title: DPA 4099 Intrument Mics & 4000 Reference Standard Microphones

media:group.media:description: This is our second interview with Ken Kimura from DPA. These Danish microphone manufacturers are certainly keeping us all on our toes with another big batch of mics released in the past year. Not only have they finished the magnificent 4099 supercardioid instrument condenser mic series, with the new drum and piano mics (Ken goes into some nice detail here for a couple of minutes), but the revamped 4000 series of Reference Standard microphones is now modular! With improved electronics in the preamplifier sections, and a new compact preamp, the choice is now yours for how to grab that signature DPA sound on classy stages, in studios and on location. ALSO announced is the all new 2000 series, coming in at a lower price. For existing 4006 users, bring your old mic into Factory Sound and compare with the new 4006A - and trust your ears. For more information, hit http://www.factorysound.com and search for DPA.

entry.title: Interview with Hermann Vega-Savon (CEO of RME) @ Melbourne GP 2011

media:group.media:description:
In what turned out to be more of an excellent day's socialising at the 2011 Melbourne Grand Prix, rather than an interview coup, we catch up with CEO of RME Audio, Hermann Vega Savon. Hermann is not only an avid car enthusiast, he's also a great bloke, and accidentally spills the beans on the new LadyFace from RME, not due to be released until Musikmesse 2011 (Frankfurt April 6-9, 2011). We also talked off camera about a few interesting MADI bits and pieces coming up. A thorough gentleman. Thanks for the chat Hermann.
Should you want any more info about RME, come via http://www.factorysound.com and get in touch. Cheers, and thanks for watching
Interview with Hermann Vega-Savon (RME) @ Melbourne GP 2011

media:group.media:description: Presonus Studio Channel - It's almost stoopidly well-featured for the small amount of $$ you'd spend on one of these. As usual, when we put 'product promo' in the title, it's because we're doing a little promotion on this one - if you're already a signed up member of Factory Sound Footy Tipping $2011, then you're in luck as we're giving away a Presonus Studio Channel this week to our best tipper. For more information on the ripper little studio channel, or on how to hook in to our competition, head on over to http://www.factorysound.com Cheers! And thanks for watching.

entry.title: Update - Wireless Spectrum in Australia, with Jeff MacKenzie

media:group.media:description:
This is a follow-up to last year's interview with Jeff MacKenzie. Last year we learnt about the imminent changes to our UHF spectrum for wireless microphone users. Although there is no firm word about what or when just yet, Jeff is able to talk us through not only what has happened in USA when they 'sold off' the 700 MHz range, but as he is the technical advisor to AWAG (Australian Wireless Audio Group), he's also able to give us a great insight into the different possibilities we may be facing as wireless microphone users. To see the original video from 2010, go here: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FdmKbi8SqAQ
And to keep up with the latest news for anything related to wireless audio in Australia, make sure you keep in touch with Factory Sound - http://www.factorysound.com
A big thanks to Jeff MacKenzie.
media:group.media:keywords: factory, sound, jands, wireless, spectrum, update, 700, mhz, whitespace, device, digital, television, broadcast, reallocation, 2013, jeff, mackenzie, professional, audio, live
media:group.media:title: Update - Wireless Spectrum in Australia, with Jeff MacKenzie

It's based around the legendary RE20, but with a neodymium magnet, and a switch for voice filter (flat) or some dips and peaks that are perfect for kick drum use. If you want any more info on RE320 - especially more serious info that what you've seen here, hit http://www.factorysound.com and search for RE320. Cheers!

media:group.media:description:
Kings of the mid-priced, powered nearfield studio monitors - the Fostex PM05MkII. We've been asked so many times: I want to improve my studio monitors, and I've got $xxx to spend... the answer is usually "mix it on PM05".
So it got us thinking about another promo clip. If you've been following any of these Factory Sound Promo Clips, you'll know that we love nothing better than a song parody, mixed with a some amateurly choregraphed dance moves, and topped off by a dash of lippy.
On a more serious note, PM05MkII are a great little powered monitor for the home and project studio. They sound great for a little edit suite too. For more serious info, head over to http://www.factorysound.com

media:group.media:description: One of our all-time favourite powered speaker boxes - the mighty RCF ART310A. So we started thinking - even though we normally do our 'product promo clips' for new (or fairly new) products, we're busting one out for the old-faithful speaker we love so much. Some of our favourite things are all together in this clip - a parody of a Queen song, Freddie with a false moustache, Hugh makes a return, Neville hams it up, and (of course) the ART310A. For more serious information about Art310A, head on over to http://www.factorysound.com

entry.title: Shure Axient Wireless - Pre Release Demo @ SMPTE 2011

media:group.media:description: We took this footage during our recent visit to SMPTE, held in July 2011 at Sydney's Darling Harbour. Shure's Axient Wireless system looks to be very impressive, and full of 'party tricks' - all especially relevant as the big frequency squeeze looms in Australia with the proposed 700 MHz sell-off. Shure has addressed that, and come up with an ingenious system as their new flagship product for high-end applications. Axient provides a huge advance, with frequency diversity, advanced interference detection and avoidance, plus remote control of transmitter. Huh? There's a bit to swallow there, probably easier just to have a squiz at the video! For more information on Shure Axient, stay in touch with us at http://www.factorysound.com - as soon as we get more information (including pricing and delivery dates), we'll keep you up-to-date. Thanks for watching.
media:group.media:keywords: factory, sound, shure, axient, wireless, system, uhf, frequency, diversity, advanced, interference, detection, and, avoidance
media:group.media:title: Shure Axient Wireless - Pre Release Demo @ SMPTE 2011

media:group.media:description: We came upon the new QSC KLA speaker system whilst visiting ENTEC 2011. This active (powered) line-array is pole mountable, ground stackable, and can also be flown. In this clip we get a brief overview of some of the nice features, including some control on the back panel, talk of the 1000w amplifier, all while imagining various applications. We've been big fans of both the K-Series, and the wooden cabinets of the KW-Series by QSC and so it's naturally exciting for us to see another new release from 'The House of K' To keep up with the latest on any new developments with these boxes, head on over to http://www.factorysound.com Thanks for watching
